# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: frederick-soddy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] The **1921 Nobel Prize in Literature** was awarded to the French author Anatole France (1844–1924) "in recognition of his brilliant literary achievements, characterized as they are by a nobility of style, a profound human sympathy, grace, and a true Gallic temperament".
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Anatole France (pseudonym for Jacques-Anatole-François Thibault) started writing poems in the classical tradition, but became known for his prose works.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] His stories and novels are noted for wit and irony, scepticism, social preoccupations and clarity in the classical tradition.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Notable works include the four volume novel sequence collected under the title *L'Histoire contemporaine* ("A Chronicle of Our Own Times", 1897–1901).
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] His famous oeuvres include *Le Crime de Sylvestre Bonnard* ("The Crime of Sylvestre Bonnard", 1881), *La Rôtisserie de la reine Pédauque* ("At the Sign of the Reine Pédauque", 1892), *Les dieux ont soif* ("The Gods Are Athirst", 1912) and *La Révolte des anges* ("The Revolt of the Angels", 1914).
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Anatole France was nominatad 13 times since 1904 before he was awarded.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] He was first introduced for the Nobel Prize by French politician Marcellin Berthelot.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] In 1921, three nominations from Erik Staaff, Johan Vising and Emanuel Walberg was submitted for him to the Nobel committee.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] In total, the Nobel Committee received 18 nominees which included Arno Holz, Arne Garborg, Gunnar Gunnarsson, W.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Yeats (awarded in 1923), George Bernard Shaw (awarded in 1925), Grazia Deledda (awarded in 1926), Henri Bergson (awarded in 1927) and John Galsworthy (awarded in 1932).
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Five of the nominees were newly nominated: Jacinto Benavente (awarded in 1922), Jean Revel, Émile Boutroux, Stefan Zeromski, and H.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Deledda was the only female nominee during this year.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] The authors Jean Aicard, Eduardo Acevedo Díaz, Hester A.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Benedict, Maximilian Berlitz, Alexander Blok, Luca Caragiale, Georges Darien, Georges Feydeau, Otto von Gierke, Rosetta Luce Gilchrist, Nikolai Gumilev, John Habberton, Sarah Dyer Hobart, E.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Hornung, Pavol Országh Hviezdoslav, Maria I.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Johnston, Peter Kropotkin, Jeanne Lapauze, Lillian Rozell Messenger, Emilia Pardo Bazán, Abba Goold Woolson and Maria Amália Vaz de Carvalho died in 1921 without having been nominated.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Anatole France had long been mentioned in the press as a popular choice for the Nobel prize.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Later Anatole France's left wing political views was also held against him by Wirsén.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Following the deliberations in 1921, four members of the the Nobel committee recommended that the 1921 prize should be awarded to the English novelist John Galsworthy.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] But committee member Henrik Schück opposed the proposal, saying: "I believe I am not wrong in assuming that this proposal was put forward without enthusiasm.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] Schück stated that among the English-language writers nominated he would place William Butler Yeats (subsequently awarded in 1923) much higher than Galsworthy.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] According to one, an entire career of an author should be rewarded, according to the other, a single, recently published masterpiece.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] If we now compare Anatole France and Galsworthy from the former point of view, there can be no doubt that Anatole France is the great author, Galsworthy the respectable mediocre.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] If we take the second point of view again, then perhaps someone could put *In Chancery* above *Le petit Pierre*.
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] On 10 November 1921, the Swedish Academy decided that that year's Nobel Prize in Literature should be awarded to Anatole France "in recognition of his brilliant literary achievements, characterized as they are by a nobility of style, a profound human sympathy, grace, and a true Gallic temperament".
[src:frederick-soddy/1921-nobel-prize-in-literature] John Galsworthy was subsequently awarded the 1932 Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover was born in Haifa, Israel on 1 October 1947 into a Jewish family.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] He is the son of Bluma (Lubashevsky), a teacher of English, and Yitzhak Ciechanover, an office worker in a law firm.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] His parents immigrated to Israel from Poland in the 1920s.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] Upon graduating from high school, Ciechanover joined the Academic Reserve (*Atuda*) and studied medicine at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] He earned a master's degree in science in 1971 and graduated from Hadassah Medical School in Jerusalem in 1974.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] He received his doctorate in biochemistry in 1981 from the Technion – Israel Institute of Technology in Haifa before conducting postdoctoral research in the laboratory of Harvey Lodish at the Whitehead Institute at MIT from 1981 to 1984.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover is currently a Technion Distinguished Research Professor in the Ruth and Bruce Rappaport Faculty of Medicine and Research Institute at the Technion.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] He is a member of the Israel Academy of Sciences and Humanities, the Pontifical Academy of Sciences, the National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine, the Russian Academy of Sciences and is a foreign associate of the United States National Academy of Sciences.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] In 2008, he was a visiting Distinguished Chair Professor at NCKU, Taiwan.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] As part of Shenzhen's 13th Five-Year Plan funding research in emerging technologies and opening "Nobel laureate research labs", in 2018 he opened the Ciechanover Institute of Precision and Regenerative Medicine at the Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen campus.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover is one of Israel's first Nobel Laureates in science, earning his Nobel Prize in 2004 for his work in ubiquitination.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] He is honored for playing a central role in the history of Israel and in the history of the Technion – Israel Institute of Technology.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover has served on the scientific advisory boards of the following companies: Rosetta Genomics (Chairman), BioLineRx, Ltd, StemRad, Ltd, Allosterix Ltd, Proteologics, Inc, MultiGene Vascular Systems, Ltd, Protalix BioTherapeutics, BioTheryX, Inc., and Haplogen, GmbH.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-ciechanover] Ciechanover is a member of the advisory board of Patient Innovation, a nonprofit, international, multilingual, free venue for patients and caregivers of any disease to share their innovations.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Klug was born in Želva, in Lithuania, to Jewish parents Lazar, a cattleman, and Bella (née Silin) Klug, with whom he emigrated to South Africa at the age of two.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Paul de Kruif's 1926 book, *Microbe Hunters*, aroused his interest in microbiology.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Klug was part of the Hashomer Hatzair Jewish Zionist youth movement in South Africa.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He started to study microbiology, but then moved into physics and maths, graduating with a Bachelor of Science degree at the University of the Witwatersrand, in Johannesburg.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] James and obtained his Master of Science degree at the University of Cape Town.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He was awarded an 1851 Research Fellowship from the Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851, which enabled him to move to England, completing his PhD in research physics at Trinity College, Cambridge in 1953.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Following his PhD, Klug moved to Birkbeck College in the University of London in late 1953, and started working with chemist and X-ray crystallographer Rosalind Franklin in the lab of crystallographer John Bernal.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] This experience aroused a lifelong interest in the study of viruses, and during his time there he made discoveries in the structure of the tobacco mosaic virus.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] In 1962 he moved to the newly built Medical Research Council (MRC) Laboratory of Molecular Biology (LMB) in Cambridge.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He studied the structure of transfer RNA, and found what is known as zinc fingers as well as the neurofibrils in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Also in 1962, Klug became a Fellow of Peterhouse, Cambridge.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He was later made an Honorary Fellow of the college.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Between 1986 and 1996, Klug was director of the LMB.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He served on the Advisory Council for the Campaign for Science and Engineering.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He also served on the Board of Scientific Governors at The Scripps Research Institute.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He and Dai Rees approached the Wellcome Trust to found the Wellcome Sanger Institute, which was a key player in the Human Genome Project.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Klug was awarded the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize from Columbia University in 1981.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He was knighted by Elizabeth II in 1988.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] In 1969 he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS), the oldest national scientific institution in the world.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He was elected its President (PRS) from 1995 to 2000.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He was appointed to the Order of Merit in 1995 – as is customary for Presidents of the Royal Society.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] In 2000, Klug received the Golden Plate Award of the American Academy of Achievement.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] In 2005, he was awarded South Africa's Order of Mapungubwe (gold) for exceptional achievements in medical science.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He was elected a Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences (FMedSci), also in 2005.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] In 2013, Israel's Ben-Gurion University of the Negev dedicated their centre for structural biology in Klug's name, *Aaron Klug Integrated Centre for Biomolecular Structure*.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He, his family and the then-British Ambassador to Israel Matthew Gould, were in attendance.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Klug was associated with the university and the town of Be'er Sheva, having visited them numerous times.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Klug married Liebe Bobrow in 1948; they had two sons, one of whom predeceased them in 2000.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] He died on 20 November 2018 in Cambridge.
[src:frederick-soddy/aaron-klug] Though Klug had faced discrimination in South Africa, he remained religious and according to Sydney Brenner, he became more religious in his older age.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Founded in 1872 as **University College Wales, Aberystwyth**, it became a founder member of the University of Wales in 1894, and changed its name to the **University College of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In the mid-1990s, the university again changed its name to become the **University of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] On 1 September 2007, the University of Wales ceased to be a federal university and Aberystwyth University became independent again.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The annual income of the institution for 2024–2025 was £124.8 million of which £19.2 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £130.3 million.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In the middle of the 19th century, eminent Welsh people were advocating the establishment of a university in the principality of Wales.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] One of these, Thomas Nicholas, whose book, *Middle and High Class Schools, and University Education for Wales* (1863), is said to have "exerted great influence on educated Welshmen".
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Funded through public and private subscriptions, and with five regional committees (London, Manchester, Liverpool, North and South Wales) guaranteeing funds for the first three years' running costs, the university opened in October 1872 with 26 students.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Thomas Charles Edwards was the principal.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In October 1875, chapels in Wales raised the next tranche of funds from over 70,000 contributors.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Until 1893, when the college joined the University of Wales as a founder member, students applying to Aberystwyth sat the University of London's entrance exams.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 1885, a fire damaged what is now known as the Old College, Aberystwyth, and in 1897 the first 14 acres of what became the main Penglais campus were purchased.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Incorporated by royal charter in 1893, the university installed Albert Edward, Prince of Wales, as chancellor in 1896, the same year it awarded an honorary degree to the former British prime minister, William Gladstone.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The university's coat of arms dates from the 1880s.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The shield features two red dragons to symbolise Wales, and an open book to symbolise learning.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The crest, an eagle or phoenix above a flaming tower, may signify the college's rebirth after the 1885 fire.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The motto is *Nid Byd, Byd Heb Wybodaeth* ('a world without knowledge is no world at all').
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In the early 1900s, the university added courses that included law, applied mathematics, pure mathematics and botany.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Department for International Politics, which Aberystwyth says is the oldest such department in the world, was founded in 1919.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] By 1977, the university's staff included eight Fellows of the Royal Society, such as Gwendolen Rees, the first Welsh woman to be elected an FRS.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Sports and Exercise Science was established in 2000.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Joint honours psychology degrees were introduced in September 2007, and single honours psychology in 2009.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The chancellor of the university is Dame Nicola Davies, who took up the position in January 2025.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The visitor of the university is an appointment made by the privy council, under the royal charter of the university.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Since July 2014, the holder of this office is Sir Roderick Evans.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2011, the university appointed a new vice chancellor under whom the academic departments were restructured as larger subject-themed institutes.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2022, the university celebrated its 150th anniversary, being established in 1872 (known at the time as The University College of Wales).
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Sciences (IBERS) is a research and teaching centre which brings together staff from the Institutes of Rural Sciences and Biological Sciences and the Institute of Grassland and Environmental Research (IGER).
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Around 360 research, teaching and support staff conduct basic, strategic and applied research in biology.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The institute is located in two areas; one at the main teaching Penglais campus and another rural research hub at the Gogerddan campus.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 1998, the Department of Economics (founded in 1912), the Department of Accounting and Finance (founded in 1979) and the Centre for Business Studies merged to create the School of Management and Business.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the School joined the Department of Information Studies and the Department of Law and Criminology at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The school was shortlisted for "Business School of the Year" in the *Times Higher Education* Awards (2014).
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2016, the institute, minus the Department of Information Studies, was renamed the Institute of Business and Law, the remaining departments being renamed Aberystwyth Business School and Aberystwyth Law School.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Computer Science (founded in 1970), conducts research in automated reasoning, computational biology, vision graphics and visualisation and intelligent robotics.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] AberMUD, the first popular internet-based MUD, was written in the department by then-student Alan Cox.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Jan Pinkava, another graduate, won an Oscar for his short animated film *Geri's Game*.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Geography and Earth Sciences (IGES) was formed, in 1989, from the former Departments of Geography (established in 1918) and Geology.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Bowen map library, containing 80,000 maps and 500 atlases.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The College of Librarianship Wales (CLW) was established at Llanbadarn Fawr in 1964, in response to a recommendation for the training of bilingual librarians that was made in the Bourdillon Report on *Standards of public library service in England* (HMSO, 1962).
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The college grew rapidly, developing close links to the Welsh speaking and professional communities, acquiring an international reputation and pioneering flexible and distance learning courses.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] It claimed to be Europe's largest institution for training librarians.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The independent college merged with the university in August 1989 and the department moved to the Penglais campus a quarter of a century later.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Following the merger, the new department took over responsibility for existing offerings in archives administration and modern records management.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Department of International Politics is the oldest of its kind in the world.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] It was founded, shortly after the First World War in 1919, with the stated purpose of furthering political understanding of the world in the hope of avoiding such conflicts in the future.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] This goal led to the creation of the Woodrow Wilson Chair of International Politics, with Wilson having played a significant role in its creation.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 700 students from 40 countries studying at undergraduate, masters and PhD levels.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] It achieved a 95% score for student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey, placing it as the highest-ranking politics department in Wales and within the UK's top ten.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The department has hosted notable academic staff in the field including E.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Carr, Leopold Kohr, Andrew Linklater, Ken Booth, Steve Smith, Michael Cox, Michael MccGwire, Jenny Edkins and Colin J.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Law and Criminology (founded in 1901) is housed in the Hugh Owen Building on the Penglais campus, and includes the *Centre for Welsh Legal Affairs*, a specialist research centre.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] All academic staff are engaged in research, and the *International Journal of Biosciences and the Law* and the *Cambrian Law Review* are edited in the department.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the department joined the Department of Information Studies and the School of Management and Business at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr, as part of a newly created Institute of Management, Law and Information Studies.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In September 2018, the department moved back to the Hugh Owen Building, based in the Penglais campus, and its name changed from Aberystwyth Law School to the Department of Law and Criminology.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth has taught modern languages since 1874.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] French, German, Italian and Spanish courses are taught at both beginners' and advanced levels, in a research-active academic environment.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] One of its research projects is the *Anglo-Norman Dictionary*, based in Aberystwyth since 2001 and available online since 2005.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Physics was first taught at Aberystwyth as part of Natural Philosophy, Astronomy and Mathematics under N.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Grimley, soon after the foundation of the University College.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] It became a department in 1877, under the leadership of F.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The department was located in the south wing of what is now the Old College, but later moved to the Physics Building on the Penglais Campus.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The first chair in Physics was offered to D.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Before the First World War, much of the early research in the department was undertaken in Germany.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Early research in the 1900s was concerned with electrical conductivity and quantum theory, later moving into thermal conductivity and acoustics.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 1931, the department hosted the Faraday Centenary Exhibition.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Williams was appointed to the Chair of Physics in 1938 where he continued his research into sub-atomic particles using a cloud chamber.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Following the Second World War, research was concerned with mechanical and nuclear physics, later moving into the fields of air density, experimental rocket launching equipment and radar.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, Aberystwyth established psychology as a "Centre for Applied Psychology" within the Department of International Politics.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] By 2011, psychology had moved into its current premises in Penbryn 5 on the Penglais Campus.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 550 undergraduate students, with degrees accredited by the British Psychological Society and is home to an MSc in Behaviour Change.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The main campus of the university is situated on Penglais Hill, overlooking the town of Aberystwyth and Cardigan Bay, and comprises most of the university buildings, Arts Centre, Students' Union, and many of the student residences.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Just below Penglais Campus is the National Library of Wales, one of Britain's five legal deposit libraries.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The landscaping of the Penglais Campus is historically significant and is listed at Grade II* on the Cadw/ICOMOS Register of Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest in Wales.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Llanbadarn Centre is located approximately one mile to the east of the Penglais Campus, near Llanbadarn Fawr, overlooking the town and Cardigan Bay to the west, with the backdrop of the Cambrian Mountains to the east.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Llanbadarn Centre hosted Aberystwyth Law School and Aberystwyth Business School, which together formed the Institute of Business and Law.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Information Studies is also based there.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Additionally, the Llanbadarn Campus is the site of the Aberystwyth branch of Coleg Ceredigion (a further education college, and not part of the university).
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] At Gogerddan, on the outskirts of town is located the university's major centre for research in land based sciences and the main centre for the Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Science.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The School of Art is located between the Penglais Campus and the centre of Aberystwyth, in what was originally the Edward Davies Memorial Chemistry Laboratories.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] A listed building, the Edward Davies Building is one of the finest examples of architecture in Aberystwyth.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The site of the original university is the Old College, currently the subject of the "New Life for Old College" project which aims to transform it into an integrated centre of heritage, culture, learning and knowledge exchange.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The university opened an international campus in Mauritius in 2015 operating as *Aberystwyth University (Mauritian Branch Campus)* and registered with the Tertiary Education Commission of Mauritius, but closed it to new enrolments two years later due to low enrolment numbers.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Less than 200 students enrolled with the Mauritius campus, which had the capacity for 2,000 students, before its 2018 closure and the university lost more than a million pounds as a result of the venture.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Most of the student residences are on campus, with the rest in walking distance of the campus and Aberystwyth town centre.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Accommodation ranges from "traditional" catered residences to en-suite self-catered accommodation, and from budget rooms to more luxurious studio apartments.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] All have wired access to the university's computer network and a support network of residential tutors.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Disabled access rooms are available within the existing student village.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University is placed in the UK's top 40 universities in the main national rankings.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] It is ranked 38th for 132 UK university rankings in *The Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide* for 2023, and the first university to be given the prestigious award "University of the year for teaching quality" for two consecutive years, in 2018 and 2019.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* placed it in the 301—350 group for 800 university rankings, compared with 351—400 the previous year, and the *QS World University Rankings* placed it at the 432nd position for 2019, compared with 481—490 of the previous year.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2015, UK employers from "predominantly business, IT and engineering sectors" listed Aberystwyth equal 49th in their 62-place employability rankings for UK graduates, according to a *Times Higher Education* report.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was rated in the top ten of UK higher education institutions for overall student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey (NSS).
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was shortlisted in four categories in the *Times Higher Education* Leadership and Management Awards (THELMAs) (2015).
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University has been awarded the Silver Award under the Corporate Health Standard (CHS), the quality mark for workplace health promotion run by Welsh Government.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The university has been awarded an Athena SWAN Charter Award, recognising commitment to advancing women's careers in science, technology, engineering, maths and medicine (STEMM) in higher education and research.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, the university came under criticism for its record on sustainability, ranking 97th out of 106 UK higher education institutions in that year's Green League table.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2012 the university was listed in the table's "Failed, no award" section, ranking equal 132nd out of 145.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2013 it ranked equal 135th out of 143, and was listed again as "Failed, no award".
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Following the university's initiatives to address sustainability, it received an EcoCampus Silver Phase award in October 2014.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In October 2015, the university's Penglais Campus became the first university campus in Wales to achieve the Green Flag Award.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The Green Flag Award is a UK-wide partnership, delivered in Wales by Keep Wales Tidy with support from Natural Resources Wales, and is the mark of a high quality park or green space.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the University and College Union alleged bullying behaviour by Aberystwyth University managers, and said staff were fearful for their jobs.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The singer Peter Karrie resigned his honorary fellowship in protest, he said, at the apparent determination to "ruin one of the finest arts centres in the country", and because he was "unable to support any regime that can treat their staff in such a cruel and appalling manner".
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] In Autumn 2024, students protested the reduction of opening hours at Hugh Owen Library, a cost-cutting measure.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] Students argued that the university had continued to promote their 24/7 Library until recent open days, and that they were going back on promises which had attracted many students to the University.
[src:frederick-soddy/aberystwyth-university] The University initially met with students to discuss options to restore the library's original opening hours, but later rejected further requests for meetings, and refused to negotiate any further.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Ada Hitchins was born on 26 June 1891 in Tavistock, Devon, England, the daughter of William Hedley Hitchins, a supervisor of customs and excise, and his wife Annie Sarah Pearsons.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] The family lived for a time in Campbeltown, Scotland, where Hitchins attended high school, graduating in 1909.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] From there, she went to the University of Glasgow, obtaining her bachelor's degree in science, with honors, in 1913.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] She was awarded prizes in botany and geology, as well as being accorded special distinction for her work in chemistry.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] In her final year at the University of Glasgow, Hitchins began to work with Frederick Soddy.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] When he moved to the University of Aberdeen as the Chair of Chemistry in 1914, Hitchins and another assistant, John A.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] At Aberdeen, Hitchins was a Carnegie Research Scholar, receiving a one-year appointment and monetary award given to a graduate of a Scottish institution for research and study by American philanthropist Andrew Carnegie.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Expectations that Soddy would establish a thriving research center at Aberdeen were disrupted by World War I, as male students became soldiers, and women students were encouraged to graduate from accelerated courses so as to fill positions in industry and government.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins was drafted to work in the Admiralty Steel Analysis Laboratories in 1916.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] After the war, women workers were displaced from their jobs by returning soldiers.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins, released from the Admiralty, was able to find work at a Sheffield steel works.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] In 1921, Frederick Soddy, then at the University of Oxford, obtained funding to rehire Hitchins as a technical assistant.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] He had recently received the Nobel prize for his work on radioactivity and isotopes.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] In 1922, Hitchins became his private research assistant.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] She continued to work with him until 1927, when she emigrated to Kenya to be nearer to her family.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins worked with Soddy over a period of 15 years, which included his most productive periods of achievement.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] She was his primary research assistant, and the only person to work with him for a long period of time.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Her careful preparation of radioactive materials, and her painstaking experimental work with uranium, protactinium, and lead isotopes, made crucial contributions to the research for which Soddy received the Nobel Prize.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] When Hitchins first worked with Soddy, researchers were still searching for new chemical elements, and isotopes were not yet understood.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] As early as 1904, researchers had hypothesized that the decay of uranium resulted in the creation of radium, but how this occurred was not clear.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] In 1907, the American radiochemist Bertram Boltwood had isolated what he believed to be a new intermediate element in the decay chain between uranium and radium, "ionium".
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Researchers eventually determined that ionium was actually an isotope of thorium, 230Th.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Soddy asked Hitchins to investigate ionium.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] She selectively extracted uranium from ore samples to create purified uranium preparations and established a half-life for ionium.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Her research also showed that there was a steady rate of increase in the amount of radium in her uranium solutions, the first direct experimental evidence that radium was formed by the decay of uranium.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins helped to determine the atomic weight of lead based on measurements of radioactive ores, work that was important in developing an understanding of isotopes.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] The samples of distilled lead which Hitchins prepared from Ceylon thorite were used by Frederick Soddy and supplied by him to Otto Hönigschmid, who did important work confirming that the atomic weight of thorium lead is higher than that of common lead.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Soddy indicated that Hitchins also worked on the actual analyses, in his published report of 1917: "According to analyses by Miss A.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins and myself, the 20 kilos of selected thorite worked upon contained 0-4 per cent, of lead, 57 per cent, of thorium, 1-03 per cent, of uranium, and 0-5 c.c. of helium per gram." This work proved that atomic weight was not a constant.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Chemically pure elements could be mixtures of isotopes with differing atomic weights.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Cranston, who had also come from Glasgow to Aberdeen with Soddy as a research assistant, was drafted in March 1915.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins continued Cranston's research before she herself was drafted for war work in 1916.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] This research resulted in the successful identification of a new element in the decay chain between uranium-235 and actinium, later named protactinium.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] The discovery of protactinium completed the early version of the periodic table proposed by Dmitri Mendeleev, who predicted the existence of an element between thorium and uranium in 1871.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] The same isotope, 231Pa, was independently discovered around the same time by Otto Hahn and Lise Meitner.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Soddy and Cranston published their paper in 1918.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] In her early work with Soddy, Hitchins helped to prepare radium standards for the calibration of gold-leaf electroscopes, used to measure radioactivity.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] After she returned to work with Soddy in 1921, Hitchins further refined measurements of the half-life of ionium, and determined ratios of thorium isotopes in mineral samples.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] She also developed methods for extracting radioactive elements from minerals and ores.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] In 1927 Hitchins moved to Kenya, to join other members of her family who had emigrated there.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Frederick Soddy wrote to the British Colonial Office, recommending her for a government position.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins was employed as a Government Assayer and Chemist in the Mining and Geological Department of the Colonial Government until 1946.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] In 1946, Hitchins married a farmer, John Ross Stephens (also spelled Rees).
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-hitchins] Hitchins died in Bristol, England, on January 4, 1972.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] In 2009, Yonath received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry along with Venkatraman Ramakrishnan and Thomas A.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Ada Lifshitz (later Yonath) was born in the Geula quarter of Jerusalem.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Her parents, Hillel and Esther Lifshitz, were Zionist Jews who immigrated to the British Mandate of Palestine (now Israel) from Zduńska Wola, Poland in 1933 before the establishment of Israel.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Her father was a rabbi and came from a rabbinical family.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] They settled in Jerusalem and ran a grocery, but found it difficult to make ends meet.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] They lived in cramped quarters with several other families, and Yonath remembers "books" being the only thing she had to keep her occupied.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Despite their poverty, her parents sent her to school in the upscale Beit HaKerem neighborhood to assure her a good education.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] When her father died at the age of 42, the family moved to Tel Aviv.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Yonath was accepted to Tichon Hadash high school although her mother could not pay the tuition.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] She gave math lessons to students in return.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] As a youngster, she says she was inspired by the Polish and naturalized-French scientist Marie Curie.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] However, she stresses that Curie, whom she as a child was fascinated by after reading her biography, was not her "role model".
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] She returned to Jerusalem for college, graduating from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem with a bachelor's degree in chemistry in 1962, and a master's degree in biochemistry in 1964.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] In 1968, she obtained her PhD from the Weizmann Institute of Science for X-ray crystallographic studies on the structure of collagen, with Wolfie Traub as her PhD advisor.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] She has one daughter, Hagit Yonath, a doctor at Sheba Medical Center, and a granddaughter, Noa.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] She is the cousin of anti-occupation activist Ruchama Marton.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Yonath accepted postdoctoral positions at Carnegie Mellon University (1969) and MIT (1970).
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] While a postdoc at MIT she spent some time in the lab of subsequent 1976 chemistry Nobel Prize winner William N.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Lipscomb, Jr. of Harvard University where she was inspired to pursue very large structures.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] In 1970, she established what was for nearly a decade the only protein crystallography laboratory in Israel.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Then, from 1979 to 1984 she was a group leader with Heinz-Günter Wittmann at the Max Planck Institute for Molecular Genetics in Berlin.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] She was a visiting professor at the University of Chicago in 1977–78.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] She headed a Max-Planck Institute Research Unit at DESY in Hamburg, Germany (1986–2004) in parallel to her research activities at the Weizmann Institute.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Yonath focuses on the mechanisms underlying protein biosynthesis, by ribosomal crystallography, a research line she pioneered over twenty years ago despite considerable skepticism of the international scientific community.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Ribosomes translate RNA into protein and because they have slightly different structures in microbes, when compared to eukaryotes, such as human cells, they are often a target for antibiotics.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] In 2000 and 2001, she determined the complete high-resolution structures of both ribosomal subunits and discovered within the otherwise asymmetric ribosome, the universal symmetrical region that provides the framework and navigates the process of polypeptide polymerization.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Consequently, she showed that the ribosome is a ribozyme that places its substrates in stereochemistry suitable for peptide bond formation and for substrate-mediated catalysis.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] In 1993 she visualized the path taken by the nascent proteins, namely the ribosomal tunnel, and recently revealed the dynamics elements enabling its involvement in elongation arrest, gating, intra-cellular regulation and nascent chain trafficking into their folding space.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] For enabling ribosomal crystallography Yonath introduced a novel technique, cryo bio-crystallography, which became routine in structural biology and allowed intricate projects otherwise considered formidable.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] At the Weizmann Institute, Yonath is the incumbent of the Martin S. and Helen Kimmel Professorial Chair.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] She has called for the unconditional release of all Palestinian prisoners, saying that "holding Palestinians captive encourages and perpetuates their motivation to harm Israel and its citizens ... once we don't have any prisoners to release they will have no reason to kidnap soldiers".
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] Yonath is a member of the United States National Academy of Sciences; the American Academy of Arts and Sciences; the Israel Academy of Sciences and Humanities; the European Academy of Sciences and Art and the European Molecular Biology Organization.
[src:frederick-soddy/ada-yonath] On Saturday, 18 October 2014, Professor Yonath was named an ordinary member of the Pontifical Academy of Sciences by Pope Francis.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] Born in Lehe, near Bremerhaven, he started his studies at Marburg University.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] For his PhD, he joined the working group of the Nobel laureate Adolf Windaus at the University of Göttingen and he finished his studies with a PhD in chemistry in 1927.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] His doctoral research was on the chemistry of the insecticidal toxin found in the roots of *Derris elliptica* which he isolated and characterized.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] After his Habilitation he became lecturer in Göttingen 1931.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] He became a professor ordinarius at the Technical University of Danzig from 1933 until 1936.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] In 1933, Butenandt signed the *Vow of allegiance of the Professors of the German Universities and High-Schools to Adolf Hitler and the National Socialistic State*.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] In 1936, he applied for the directorship of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institut (later the Max Planck Institute for Biochemistry) in Berlin-Dahlem while also joining the NSDAP on 1 May 1936 (party member No.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] The earlier director of the Kaiser Wilhelm institute was Carl Neuberg, who had been removed for being a Jew.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] His work on rotenones was considered useful by the Nazi leadership as it could be useful for controlling lice among soldiers in the trenches.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] As the head of a leading institute, he applied for government funding on concentrated research labeled *kriegswichtig* (important for the war), some of which focused on military projects like the improvement of oxygen uptake for high-altitude bomber pilots.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] Adolf Windaus and Walter Schöller of Schering gave him the advice to work on hormones extracted from ovaries.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] This research lead to the discovery of estrone and other primary female sex hormones, which were extracted from several thousand liters of urine.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] In 1940 he was involved in research on a hormone treatment to make long submarine voyages more comfortable for submariners in the Kriegsmarine.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] Butenand's involvement with the Nazi regime and various themes of research led to criticism after the war, and even after his death the exact nature of his political orientation during the Nazi era has never been fully resolved.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] When the institute moved to Tübingen in 1945 he became a professor at the University of Tübingen.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] In 1948, he was considered for the chair for physiological medicine at the University of Basel.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] He entered in negotiations but eventually was convinced by the chemical industry to stay in Germany.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] In 1956, when the institute relocated to Martinsried, a suburb of Munich, Butenandt became a professor at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] He also served as president of the Max Planck Society for the Advancement of Science following Otto Hahn from 1960 to 1972.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] Butenandt is credited with the discovery and naming of the silkworm moth pheromone Bombykol in 1959.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] Butenandt died in Munich in 1995, at the age of 91.
[src:frederick-soddy/adolf-butenandt] His wife Erika, born in 1906, died in 1995 at 88.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Soddy was born at 6 Bolton Road, Eastbourne, England, the son of Benjamin Soddy, corn merchant, and his wife Hannah Green.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He went to school at Eastbourne College, before going on to study at University College of Wales at Aberystwyth and at Merton College, Oxford, where he graduated in 1898 with first class honours in chemistry.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He was a researcher at Oxford from 1898 to 1900.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1900, he became a demonstrator in chemistry at McGill University in Montreal, Quebec, where he worked with Ernest Rutherford on radioactivity.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He and Rutherford realized that the anomalous behaviour of radioactive elements was because they decayed into other elements.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] This decay also produced alpha, beta, and gamma radiation.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] When radioactivity was first discovered, no one was sure what the cause was.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] It needed careful work by Soddy and Rutherford to prove that atomic transmutation was in fact occurring.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1903, with Sir William Ramsay at University College London, Soddy showed that the decay of radium produced helium gas.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In the experiment a sample of radium was enclosed in a thin-walled glass envelope sited within an evacuated glass bulb.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] After leaving the experiment running for a long period of time, a spectral analysis of the contents of the former evacuated space revealed the presence of helium.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Later in 1907, Rutherford and Thomas Royds showed that the helium was first formed as positively charged nuclei of helium (He2+) which were identical to alpha particles, which could pass through the thin glass wall but were contained within the surrounding glass envelope.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] From 1904 to 1914, Soddy was a lecturer at the University of Glasgow.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Ruth Pirret worked as his research assistant during this time.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In May 1910 Soddy was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1914 he was appointed to a chair at the University of Aberdeen, where he worked on research related to World War I.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1913, Soddy showed that an atom moves lower in atomic number by two places on alpha emission, higher by one place on beta emission.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] This was discovered at about the same time by Kazimierz Fajans, and is known as the radioactive displacement law of Fajans and Soddy, a fundamental step toward understanding the relationships among families of radioactive elements.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1913 Soddy also described the phenomenon in which a radioactive element may have more than one atomic mass though the chemical properties are identical.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He named this concept isotope meaning "same place".
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] The word was initially suggested to him by Margaret Todd.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Thomson showed that non-radioactive elements can also have multiple isotopes.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] The work that Soddy and his research assistant Ada Hitchins did at Glasgow and Aberdeen showed that uranium decays to radium.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Soddy published *The Interpretation of Radium* (1909) and *Atomic Transmutation* (1953).
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1918, working with the Scottish scientist John Arnold Cranston, he announced the discovery of an isotope of the element later named protactinium.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] This slightly post-dated its discovery by the Germans Lise Meitner and Otto Hahn; however, it is said their discovery was actually made in 1915 but its announcement was delayed due to Cranston's notes being locked away whilst on active service in the First World War.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1919, he moved to the University of Oxford as the first Dr.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Lee's Professor of Chemistry, where, in the period up till 1936, he reorganized the laboratories and the syllabus in chemistry.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He received the 1921 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his research in radioactive decay and particularly for his formulation of the theory of isotopes.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In Soddy's 1922 paper "Radioactivity and the Evolution of the World" there is a section on Soddy's belief that knowledge in the form of myths had been passed down to the present day from an ancient, advanced civilisation.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] His work and essays popularising the new understanding of radioactivity was the main inspiration for H.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Wells's *The World Set Free* (1914), which features atomic bombs dropped from biplanes in a war set many years in the future.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Wells's novel is also known as *The Last War* and imagines a peaceful world emerging from the chaos.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In *Wealth, Virtual Wealth and Debt* Soddy praises Wells's *The World Set Free*.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He also says that radioactive processes probably power the stars.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In four books written from 1921 to 1934, Soddy carried on a "campaign for a radical restructuring of global monetary relationships", offering a perspective on economics rooted in physics – the laws of thermodynamics, in particular – and was "roundly dismissed as a crank".
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Soddy wrote that financial debts grew exponentially at compound interest but the real economy was based on exhaustible stocks of fossil fuels.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Energy obtained from the fossil fuels could not be used again.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] This criticism of economic growth is echoed by his intellectual heirs in the emergent field of ecological economics.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In *Wealth, Virtual Wealth and Debt,* Soddy cited the *Protocols of the Learned Elders of Zion*, which had been widely disseminated by Henry Ford in the United States, as evidence that the belief in a "financial conspiracy to enslave the world" was widespread at the time.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He further wrote that "conscious conspiracy or not ... a corrupt monetary system strikes at the very life of the nation".
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Later in life he published a pamphlet *Abolish Private Money, or Drown in Debt* (1939).
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Though some activists have insubstantially accused Soddy of anti-Semitism, most of his biographers dispute this narrative and argue that among Soddy's friends and students were some Jews who held positive views of him.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He rediscovered Descartes' theorem in 1936 and published it as a poem, "The Kiss Precise", quoted at Problem of Apollonius.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] The kissing circles in this problem are sometimes known as **Soddy circles**.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1921 and the same year was elected member of the International Atomic Weights Committee.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] A small crater on the far side of the Moon as well as the radioactive uranium mineral soddyite are named after him.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] Wells dedicated his novel *The World Set Free* to Soddy's *Interpretation of Radium* (1909).
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] In 1908, Soddy married Winifred Moller Beilby (1885–1936), the daughter of industrial chemist Sir George Beilby and Lady Emma Bielby, a philanthropist to women's causes.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] The couple worked together and co-published a paper in 1910 on the absorption of gamma rays from radium.
[src:frederick-soddy/frederick-soddy] He died in Brighton, England in 1956, twenty days after his 79th birthday.
